frameDefinitions: An Agent supports their body in a particular Location.
This frame has to do with people (the Residents) residing in Locations, sometimes with a Co-resident.
A Protagonist is in the dynamic, maintained state of being alive or has exited this state.
A Protagonist changes the overall position and posture of the body.
An Item is the only instance of its Type.
frameExamples: Smithers <t>leaned</t> forward to grab the folder on the far side.
Steven is the <t>sole</t> survivor in his family.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Agent</fen> is the individual whose body is in a particular posture.  The <fen>Agent</fen> role is generally expressed as the external argument of verbs:
A description of the position of the <fen>Agent</fen>.  The <fen>Location</fen> of the <fen>Agent</fen> is frequently expressed and generally occurs as a PP Complement:
The part of the body that provides support to the <fen>Agent</fen>'s body in the posture.
This role indicates the Time interval during which the <fen>Agent</fen> held a certain posture.
The individual(s) that reside at the <fen>Location</fen>.
The place in which somebody resides.
A person or group of people that the resident is staying with or among.
This role refers to the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Resident</fen> resides.
<fen>Protagonist</fen> identifies the being or entity that is  dead or alive.
This role identifies the <fen>Figure</fen> or form being described by the target.
The time in which the <fen>Protagonist</fen> is dead or alive.
The <fen>Time</fen> at which the <fen>Protagonist</fen> changes posture.
An <fen>Item</fen> is alone in its category.
<fen>Type</fen> specifies a category which in principle could apply to multiple items, but which is limited to the <fen>Item</fen>.
listRoleExamples: I stood <fex>on my heels</fex> and looked out the window
<fex>Yesterday evening</fex> he was sitting in his armchair as usual
